      <hedline>
        <hl1>Jerusalem's Status</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Israel M Bar-Nir says Gov George W Bush is latest in long line of presidential candidates who vow to move United States Embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem (May 23 article); says once in power, every US president so far has reneged on this promise</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Every four years during the election campaign, presidential candidates go through the motions of promising to move the United States Embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem. As you report (news article, May 23), Gov. George W. Bush has ''pledged that as president he would 'begin the process of moving the U.S. ambassador to the city Israel has chosen as its capital,' a reference to Jerusalem.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Every four years during the election campaign, presidential candidates go through the motions of promising to move the United States Embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem. As you report (news article, May 23), Gov. George W. Bush has ''pledged that as president he would 'begin the process of moving the U.S. ambassador to the city Israel has chosen as its capital,' a reference to Jerusalem.''</p>
        <p>Once in power, however, every United States president so far has reneged on this (or a similar) promise, citing a host of excuses.</p>
        <p>But there is a more serious issue than the geographical location of the embassy: Even today, half a century after the formation of the State of Israel, the United States, or at least the State Department, does not legally recognize any part of Jerusalem as being a part of Israel.</p>
        <p>ISRAEL M. BAR-NIR  Sunnyvale, Calif., May 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
